    chapter: "Advanced Math - Easy",
    title: "Advanced Math 71",
    prompt: "If $x^2 - 9 = 0$, what is the value of $x$?",
    correct: "-3 or 3",
    wrong: [["-3","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."],["3","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."],["9","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."]],
    lesson: "Source: OpenSAT (opensat::random_id_b23). We can factor the expression as a difference of squares: $(x+3)(x-3) = 0$. For this product to equal zero, one or both of the factors must equal zero. Therefore, $x + 3 = 0$ or $x - 3 = 0$, which gives us $x = -3$ or $x = 3$.",
