    chapter: "Algebra - Medium",
    title: "Algebra 74",
    prompt: "The equation $x^2+4x-9=0$ can be solved by using the quadratic formula. What is the value of the discriminant of this equation?",
    correct: "40",
    wrong: [["-40","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."],["16","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."],["64","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."]],
    lesson: "Source: OpenSAT (opensat::d6a4f412). The quadratic formula states that for the equation $ax^2 + bx + c = 0$, the discriminant is $b^2 - 4ac$. In this case, $a = 1$, $b = 4$, and $c = -9$. Therefore, the discriminant is $4^2 - 4(1)(-9) = 16 + 36 = 52$.",
