    chapter: "Advanced Math - Hard",
    title: "Advanced Math 86",
    prompt: "What is the value of the expression $$\\frac{3^{12} \\cdot 9^4}{27^3}$$?",
    correct: "3^{15}",
    wrong: [["3^9","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."],["3^{12}","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."],["3^{18}","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."]],
    lesson: "Source: OpenSAT (opensat::26f856bf). The expression can be rewritten as $\\frac{3^{12} \\cdot (3^2)^4}{(3^3)^3}$. Applying the rules of exponents, we have $\\frac{3^{12} \\cdot 3^8}{3^9}$, which simplifies to $3^{12+8-9} = 3^{11}$.",
