    title: "Geometry and Trigonometry 123",
    prompt: "A circle has a circumference of 10\\pi. What is the area of the circle?",
    correct: "25\\pi",
    wrong: [["5\\pi","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."],["10\\pi","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."],["100\\pi","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."]],
    lesson: "Source: OpenSAT (opensat::3d892d23). The circumference of a circle is given by the formula C = 2\\pi r, where r is the radius. We are given that C = 10\\pi, so 10\\pi = 2\\pi r. Dividing both sides by 2\\pi gives r = 5. The area of a circle is given by the formula A = \\pi r^2. Substituting 5 for r gives A = \\pi (5)^2 = 25\\pi.",
