    chapter: "Advanced Math - Easy",
    title: "Advanced Math 251",
    prompt: "A circle in the xy-plane has center (2, -3) and radius 5. Which of the following is an equation for this circle?",
    correct: "(x - 2)^2 + (y + 3)^2 = 25",
    wrong: [["(x + 2)^2 + (y - 3)^2 = 25","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."],["(x - 2)^2 + (y + 3)^2 = 5","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."],["(x + 2)^2 + (y - 3)^2 = 5","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."]],
    lesson: "Source: OpenSAT (opensat::1e20d548). The standard form of the equation of a circle with center (h, k) and radius r is (x - h)^2 + (y - k)^2 = r^2. Substituting the values from the problem gives us (x - 2)^2 + (y + 3)^2 = 5^2, which simplifies to (x - 2)^2 + (y + 3)^2 = 25.",
