    chapter: "Geometry and Trigonometry - Hard",
    title: "Geometry and Trigonometry 354",
    prompt: "A right triangle has legs of length 5 and 12. What is the length of the hypotenuse?",
    correct: "13",
    wrong: [["10","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."],["17","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."],["20","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."]],
    lesson: "Source: OpenSAT (opensat::1c6d5542). The Pythagorean Theorem states that in a right triangle, the square of the hypotenuse is equal to the sum of the squares of the legs. So, if the legs are 5 and 12, the hypotenuse is $\\sqrt{5^2 + 12^2} = \\sqrt{169} = 13$.",
    source: 'OpenSAT',
