    chapter: "Geometry and Trigonometry - Medium",
    title: "Geometry and Trigonometry 384",
    prompt: "A right triangle has legs of length 5 and 12. What is the length of the hypotenuse of the triangle?",
    correct: "13",
    wrong: [["17","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."],["19","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."],["25","This is one of the OpenSAT distractors, but it misses the specific evidence or calculation.","Use the passage, grammar rule, or math relationship named in the question rather than the closest-sounding option."]],
    lesson: "Source: OpenSAT (opensat::f1d7a634). The Pythagorean Theorem states that in a right triangle, the square of the hypotenuse is equal to the sum of the squares of the legs. Therefore, the length of the hypotenuse is $\\sqrt{5^2 + 12^2} = \\sqrt{169} = 13$.",
    source: 'OpenSAT',
